smooched.

17:36.472 --> 17:38.384
<i>You know what?</i>

17:38.474 --> 17:42.093
Let's take the Santa Rosa Road
exit and hit Sanford first. Okay?

17:42.186 --> 17:44.678
Sounds good to me.
I need a drink.

17:44.772 --> 17:47.685
These guys make top-notch
pinot and chardonnay.

17:47.775 --> 17:50.142
One of the best producers
in Santa Barbara County.

17:50.278 --> 17:53.191
- I thought you hated chardonnay. No, no, no.
- I like all varietals.

17:53.281 --> 17:56.865
I just don't generally like the way they
manipulate chardonnay in California.

17:56.993 --> 18:00.862
- Too much oak and secondary malolactic fermentation.
- Huh.

18:00.955 --> 18:04.869
You see, the reason that this
region is so good for pinot...

18:04.959 --> 18:08.293
is that the cold air off the
Pacific flows in at night...

18:08.379 --> 18:10.917
and it just
cools down the berries.

18:11.007 --> 18:13.841
Pinot's a very
thin-skinned grape.

18:13.926 --> 18:17.465
It doesn't like constant heat or humidity.
Very delicate.

18:20.016 --> 18:22.429
<i>Let me show
you how this is done.</i>

18:22.518 --> 18:25.431
First thing... hold the glass up and
examine the wine against the light.

18:25.521 --> 18:27.683
You're looking
for color and clarity.

18:27.815 --> 18:30.228
- Just get a sense of it. Okay?
- Okay.

18:30.318 --> 18:33.311
Thick? Thin?
Watery? Syrupy?

18:33.404 --> 18:35.270
- Okay?
- Okay.

18:35.364 --> 18:37.276
Now tip it.

18:37.366 --> 18:41.861
What you're doing here is checking for color
density as it thins out towards the rim.

18:41.954 --> 18:44.867
<i>That's gonna tell you how old it is,
among other things.</i>

18:44.957 --> 18:46.869
<i>It's usually
more important with reds.</i>

18:46.959 --> 18:48.871
- Okay?
- Okay.

18:48.961 --> 18:50.827
Now stick your nose
in it.

18:50.963 --> 18:53.376
- Yeah?
- Don't be shy.

18:53.466 --> 18:55.753
Really get your nose
right in there. Really...

18:57.386 --> 18:59.423
Mmm.
A little citrus.

19:00.473 --> 19:02.556
